'''David Gene Pearson''' (born December 22, 1934) is a former [[United States|American]] [[stock car racing|stock car racer]] from [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]].<ref name="Fleischman197" /> Pearson began his [[NASCAR]] career in 1960 and ended his first season by winning the 1960 [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year]] award.<ref name="Fleischman197" /> He won three championships (1966, 1968, and 1969) in [[NASCAR]]'s Grand National Series (now [[Sprint Cup Series]]).<ref name="Fleischman197">{{cite book|last=Fleischman|first=Bill|coauthors=Pearce, Al|title=The Unauthorized NASCAR Fan Guide (1998-99)|publisher=Visible Ink Press|location=[[Farmington Hills, Michigan]]|date=1999|pages=197|isbn=1-57859-111-2|accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> NASCAR described his 1974 season as an indication of his "consistent greatness"; that season he finished third in the season points having competed in only 19 of 30 races.<ref name="InauguarlClassOf2010Nominee" /> 

At his finalist nomination for [[NASCAR Hall of Fame]]'s inaugural 2010 class, NASCAR described Pearson as "... the model of NASCAR efficiency during his career. With little exaggeration, when Pearson showed up at a race track, he won."<ref name="InauguarlClassOf2010Nominee">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/news/features/dpearson.hof.bio/|title=Inaugural Class of 2010 Nominee: David Pearson|date=2009|publisher=[[NASCAR]]|accessdate=2009-08-23}}</ref> Pearson ended his career in 1986, and currently holds the second position on NASCAR's all-time win list with 105 victories; as well as achieving 113 [[pole position]]s.<ref name="Fleischman197" /> Pearson was successful in different venues of racing; he won three times on [[road racing|road course]]s, 48 times on [[superspeedway]]s, 54 time on [[short track racing|short tracks]], and had 23 [[dirt track racing|dirt track]] wins.<ref name="Fleischman197" /> Pearson finished with at least one Top 10 finish in each of his 27 seasons.<ref name="Fleischman197" /> Pearson was nicknamed the "Fox" (and later the "Silver Fox") for his calculated approach to racing.<ref name="Falk71">{{cite book|last=Falk|first=Duane|title=The Daytona 500:The Great American Race|publisher=Michael Friedman Publishing Group|date=2002|pages=71-72|isbn=1586631691|accessdate=2009-11-19}}</ref> ESPN described him as being a "plain-spoken, humble man, and that added up to very little charisma."<ref name="ESPNOctober162009">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=4566541&name=hinton_ed|title=Pearson's plight could be bad news for Johnson|last=Hinton|first=Ed|date=October 16, 2009|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=22 December 2009}}</ref>

Pearson's career paralleled [[Richard Petty]]'s, the winningest driver in NASCAR history.<ref name="ESPNMarch252009">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/nascar/cup/columns/story?columnist=hinton_ed&id=3995976|title=Pearson: Just drive the car|last=Hinton|first=Ed|date=March 25, 2009|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> They accounted for 63 first/second place finishes.<ref name="ESPNMarch252009" /> Petty said, "Pearson could beat you on a short track, he could beat you on a superspeedway, he could beat you on a road course, he could beat you on a dirt track. It didn't hurt as bad to lose to Pearson as it did to some of the others, because I knew how good he was."<ref name="ESPNMarch252009" />

==Background==
Pearson was born in [[Whitney, South Carolina]], near [[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]], in an area known for its [[moonshine]] roots.<ref name="Jones134" /> When Pearson was young, he climbed a tree at the local stock car racing track (Spartanburg Fairgrounds) to see the races.<ref name="Jones134" /> Pearson said, "I'd always been interested in cars, and I decided right then that was what I wanted to do with my life."<ref name="Jones134" /> He worked with his brother in a car body repair shop, and used the money to purchase a [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] coach.<ref name="Jones134" /> Pearson removed the [[Fender (vehicle)|fenders]] to convert the vehicle into a [[hot rod|street rod]].<ref name="Jones134" /> He jumped the car over ditches until he rolled it over.<ref name="Jones134" /> His mother paid him to junk the car and he used the money to purchase another car to build.<ref name="Jones134" /> In 1952, he raced a 1940 Ford at [[dirt track racing|dirt tracks]] and won $30 in an outlaw class race.<ref name="Jones134" /> He kept winning and attracted the attention of Spartanburg's racing community, including John Littlejohn.<ref name="Jones134" /> 

==Career==
===1960s===
Pearson began racing in NASCAR's Grand National series during the 1960 season<ref name="Fleischman31">Fleischman, page 31</ref> shortly after winning the 1959 track champion at [[Greenville-Pickens Speedway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenvillepickens.com/track_champions.htm|title=Track Champions|date=2009|publisher=[[Greenville-Pickens Speedway]]|accessdate=2009-10-21}}</ref> His first NASCAR start was the first 1960 [[Gatorade Duel|Daytona 500 qualifying race]] and he finished 17th in a self-owned car that he had purchased from [[Jack White (NASCAR)|Jack White]].<ref name="Fleischman307">Fleischman, page 307</ref><ref name="Jones134" /> He started 22 events that season, finishing 23rd in season points and was voted the 1960 [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year]].<ref name="Fleischman31" /> His season was highlighted by a second-place finish at [[Gamecock Speedway]] in [[Sumter, South Carolina]], and a fourth place finish at [[Hickory Motor Speedway]] and fifth after starting on the [[pole position]] at his hometown track in [[Piedmont Interstate Fairgrounds]] in Spartanburg.<ref name="Fleischman31" />

[[File:DavidPearsonPontiac.jpg|left|thumb|Pearson's 1961 [[Pontiac]], prepared by [[Ray Fox]]|alt=David Pearson's 1961 Ponitac]]
When Pearson bent the frame of the his own race car early in the 1961 season, he began working as a house roofer in Spartanburg to support his family, which included two sons.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2009/news/features/05/12/charlotte.moments.david.pearson/index.html|title=Pearson career soars after Dieringer contract dispute|last=Aumann|first=Mark|date=2009-05-12|publisher=[[NASCAR]]|accessdate=2009-08-29}}</ref> [[Darel Dieringer]] had a contract dispute with a tire company and was not able to compete in the inaugural [[Coca-Cola 600|World 600]] at [[Lowes Motor Speedway|Charlotte]]. Littlejohn was at the track, and he recommended that car builder [[Ray Fox]] hire Pearson.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Pearson was unsure if he should join the team, and Fox was not convinced that he should trust his car to relatively untested 26-year-old driver.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> After Pearson had a successful test run, he qualified the car with the third fastest time behind [[Richard Petty]] and [[Joe Weatherly]].<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Pearson raced his way into the lead early in the event and was the leader after the first round of pit stops.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Pearson and Petty were the only two cars on the lead lap by a restart on the 311th lap (of 400).<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Petty made up six seconds on Pearson in 20 laps before Petty had to retire with a blown engine.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Pearson held a three lap lead over [[Fireball Roberts]] and was leading late in the race until he ran over some debris on the backstretch and blew a tire with only two laps remaining.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> Pearson drove the car around the track slowly for the final lap at approximately {{convert|20|mph|km/h}} to take the victory.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> He started in 19 races during the 1961 season and he had three wins to finish thirteenth in season points,<ref>Fleischman, page 32</ref> winning his first NASCAR race  in a Fox-prepared car at [[Concord Speedway]].<ref name="Fleischman323">Fleischman, page 323</ref> Later in the season, he won the [[Coke Zero 400|Firecracker 250]] at [[Daytona International Speedway|Daytona]] and the [[Pep Boys Auto 500|Dixie 400]] at [[Atlanta Motor Speedway|Atlanta]].<ref name="Fleischman323" /> 

Pearson started in only 12 of 53 events in 1962 yet managed to finish tenth in season points.<ref name="Fleischman33">Fleischman, page 33</ref> Pearson began the season racing for Fox until Fox retired;<ref name="Jones134" /> he started for [[Petty Enterprises]], [[Cotton Owens]], and [[Bud Moore (NASCAR owner)|Bud Moore]] that season.<ref name="RacingReference1962">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1962&series=W|title=1962 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He had seven top ten finishes and no wins.<ref name="RacingReference1962" /> During 41 starts in 55 races, Pearson finished the 1963 season sixth in points for Cotton Owens.<ref name="RacingReference1963">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1963&series=W|title=1963 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-22}}</ref> He held two pole positions and had no wins.<ref name="Fleischman34">Fleischman, page 34</ref><ref name="RacingReferenceCareer" /> In 1964, he had eight wins at [[Richmond International Raceway|Richmond]], [[Greenville-Pickens Speedway]], [[Occoneechee Speedway]], [[Boyd Speedway]], [[Lincoln Speedway (New Oxford)|Lincoln Speedway]], Rambi Raceway (now [[Myrtle Beach Speedway]]), [[Columbia Speedway]], and [[Hickory Motor Speedway]].<ref name="Fleischman324">Fleischman, page 324-325</ref> Pearson finished third in the championship, which was won by Petty for the first time.<ref name="Fleischman324" /> He qualified on the pole position for 12 events.<ref name="RacingReferenceCareer" />

NASCAR banned the [[Mopar]] [[Hemi engine]] in 1965, so Petty and Pearson boycotted many races rather than compete with a non-competitive engine against [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] and [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]] drivers.<ref name="Fleischman35">Fleischman, page 35</ref> Both competed in drag racing. Pearson drove a [[Dodge Dart]] [[station wagon]] nicknamed the "Cotton Picker" for Owens.<ref name="ESPNTheMagazineSeptember182009">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/nascar/cup/columns/story?columnist=mcgee_ryan&id=4485331|title=Pearson looks right at home in NHRA|last=McGee|first=Ryan|date=September 18, 2009|publisher=ESPN: The magazine|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> NASCAR owner [[Bill France, Sr.]] adjusted the engine rules later in the season to bring back Mopar drivers; Petty and Pearson ended up competing in 14 of 55 events.<ref name="Fleischman35" /> Pearson won two of the final 21 races ([[Columbia Speedway|Columbia]] and [[Richmond International Raceway|Richmond]]) to finish 40th in the season points.<ref name="Fleischman35" /> 

Pearson won his the first of his three NASCAR championships in 1966.<ref name="Fleischman36">Fleischman, page 36</ref> He won 15 of 49 events, which was the second most in NASCAR history at that time.<ref name="Fleischman36" /> Early in the season, Pearson won at Hickory, Columbia, Greenville-Pickens, and [[Winston-Salem Speedway]] to complete four straight victories.<ref name="Fleischman325">Fleischman, page 325</ref><ref name="NASCAR40Years" /> Throughout the season, Pearson won at Richmond, [[Dog Track Speedway]] ([[Moyock, North Carolina]]), [[New Asheville Speedway]], [[Smokey Mountain Raceway]], the second Greenville-Pickens race, [[Bridgehampton Raceway]], [[Fonda Speedway]], Columbia, [[Bowman Gray Stadium]], Hickory, and the [[Chevy Rock and Roll 400|second Richmond race]].<ref name="Fleischman325" /> 

Pearson ran a partial season in 1967, competing in 22 of 48 races.<ref name="Fleischman36" /> He began the season racing for [[Cotton Owens]] before switching after the thirteenth race to [[Holman Moody]].<ref name="RacingReference1967">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1967&series=W|title=1967 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-22}}</ref> Pearson quit after there was a misunderstanding about who would drive the teams tow truck.<ref name="CrossWords" /> Dodge decided to stop racing in NASCAR, so Pearson switched way from Owen's Dodges in favor of Holman Moody's Fords.<ref name="NASCAR40Years" /> He had two wins (Bristol, Greenville-Pickens), both for Owens, in a season that was dominated by Petty's all-time record 27 victories (including all-time record 10 straight).<ref name="Fleischman37">Fleischman, page 37</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/20/sports/auto-racing-a-record-for-gordon-is-only-miles-away.html?scp=1&sq=%22richard+petty%22+10+straight&st=nyt|title=AUTO RACING; A Record for Gordon Is Only Miles Away|last=El-Bashir|first=Tarik|date=August 28, 1998|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref> Pearson finished seventh in season points.<ref name="Fleischman37" />

Petty and Pearson each won 16 races during 1968; Pearson won the championship and Petty finished third.<ref name="Fleischman38">Fleischman, page 38</ref> Pearson complete primarily for [[Holman-Moody]], winning at Bristol, Richmond, North Wilkesboro, [[Asheville-Weaverville Speedway]], Darlington, [[Beltsville Speedway]], [[Langley Field Speedway]], Charlotte, [[Middle Georgia Raceway]], Bristol, [[Music City Motorplex|Nashville Speedway]], Columbia, Bowman-Gray, Asheville-Weaverville, Langley Field, Hickory, and [[Augusta Speedway]].<ref name="RacingReference1968">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1968&series=W|title=1968 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He added twelve pole positions.<ref name="RacingReference1968" />

Pearson won his third and final championship in 1969.<ref name="Fleischman39">Fleischman, page 39</ref> The championship tied Pearson with [[Lee Petty]] for the most championships in NASCAR history (Richard Petty holds the current record with seven titles).<ref name="NASCAR40Years">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2009/news/features/09/09/inside.nascar.dpearson.retrospective/index.html|title=Forty years later, Pearson still seminal driver of '60s|last=Cross|first=Duane|date=September 9, 2009|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=14 December 2009}}</ref> He started out the season at the [[1969 Daytona 500]] by being the first driver to qualify faster than 190&nbsp;miles&nbsp;per&nbsp;hour with a speed of {{convert|190.029|mph|km/h}}.<ref name="Jones134">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Anne B.|coauthors=[[Rex White|White, Rex]]|title=All around the track|publisher=McFarland|date=2007|pages=134-136|isbn=0786429887|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=e9JB3ax1iPgC&pg=PT146&dq=%22david+pearson%22+nascar&lr=#v=onepage&q=%22david%20pearson%22%20nascar&f=false|accessdate=2009-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytonainternationalspeedway.com/News/DAYTONA-500-History/DAYTONA-500-Winners/1969-Daytona-500-Results.aspx|title=1969 DAYTONA 500 Results|publisher=[[Daytona International Speedway]]|accessdate=19 November 2009}}</ref> After winning the first Daytona 500 Qualifying race, Pearson led the 500 under caution with 13 laps remaining and changed only his right side tires in a two-tire pit stop. [[Pete Hamilton]] did a four-tire stop and passed Pearson after the restart for the victory.<ref name="Falk62">Falk, page 62</ref> In 51 starts, he had 11 wins, 42 top-fives, and 44 top-tens.<ref name="Fleischman39" /> He earned a record $229,760 for his effort.<ref name="Fleischman39" /> Pearson completed 14,270 laps in 1969, which is the most laps ever in a NASCAR Cup season.<ref name="Fleischman309">Fleischman, page 309</ref> He was one of eleven drivers to boycott the first race at Talladega after concerns with the tires; he rejoined the tour at the following event.<ref name="NASCAR40Years" />

===1970s===
[[File:DavidPearson17HolmanMoody.jpg|thumb|right|A Pearson [[Holman Moody]] car]]
The 1970 season started with Pearson competing part-time, like he would for the rest of his career. In 19 starts, he won a single race (Darlington) and earned two pole positions (Bristol, Darlington) to finished 23rd in points.<ref name="RacingReference1970">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1970&series=W|title=1970 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

[[R. J. Reynolds]] began sponsoring NASCAR in 1971 and the Grand National series was retitled the Winston Cup Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2007/news/headlines/cup/06/04/bfrancejr.dies.timeline/index.html|title=Timeline: Bill France Jr.|last=Rodman|first=Dave|date=June 5, 2007|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=14 February 2010}}</ref> Holman Moody and Pearson split near the middle of the season after Pearson refused to take a 10% pay cut .<ref name="RacingReference1971">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1971&series=W|title=1971 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He won two races before the split ([[Gatorade Duel|Daytona Twin 125]] and [[Food City 500|Bristol]]) plus four second place finishes.<ref name="RacingReference1971" /> Pearson finished out the season by competing in seven races for Ray Nichels.<ref name="RacingReference1971" /> He recorded one top-ten finish (eighth at the July Daytona race), but suffered mechanical problems in all of the other races.<ref name="RacingReference1971" /> For the season he finished 51st in points after competing in 17 races with nine top-tens and eight top-fives.<ref name="RacingReference1971" />

At [[R. J. Reynolds]]' request, NASCAR began cutting down on the number of races in 1972 season by eliminating midweek races.<ref name="Fleischman41">Fleischman, page 41</ref> It also dropped 13 short tracks and had a 31-race schedule.<ref name="Fleischman41" /><ref name="Fleischman54">Fleischman, page 54</ref> Pearson began racing for the [[Wood Brothers]] that season.<ref name="NASCARDavidPearson">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2002/kyn/history/drivers/02/02/dpearson/index.html|title=David Pearson|date=2003-01-22|publisher=[[NASCAR]]|accessdate=2009-08-29}}</ref> He raced in 17 of the events and had six wins, which earned him a 20th place finish in the season points.<ref name="Fleischman54" /> Pearson was racing against [[Bobby Isaac]] and [[Buddy Baker]] at the end of the [[Aaron's 499|Winston 500]] at [[Talladega Superspeedway]] when Jimmy Crawford spun into Isaac; Pearson won the race.<ref name="Fleischman54" /> He won later that season at the [[Coke Zero 400|Firecracker 400]], a race that he would win three straight times.<ref name="Falk70">Falk, page 70</ref>

While Pearson only started in 18 (of 28) races during 1973, he was named the NASCAR driver of the Year after finishing eighth in points.<ref name="Fleischman197">Fleischman, page 197</ref><ref name="NASCARDrivingStastistics" /> He won 11 of those 18 races in the Wood Brothers [[Mercury (automobile)|Mercury]].<ref name="Fleischman55">Fleischman, page 55</ref> His 61% win percentage is the highest in NASCAR history.<ref name="Fleischman311">Fleischman, page 311</ref> He had wins at [[North Carolina Motor Speedway]] (Rockingham), Atlanta, Darlington, [[Martinsville Speedway|Martinsville]], Talladega, [[Dover International Speedway|Dover]], [[Michigan International Speedway|Michigan]], second Daytona race, second Atlanta race, second Dover race, and the second Rockingham race.<ref name="NASCARStatistics1973">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/hof/dpearson00/seasons/1973.html|title=Pearson's 1973 driving statistics|publisher=[[NASCAR]]|accessdate=14 February 2010}}</ref> The remaining seven races contained four [[List_of_motorsport_terminology#D|Did Not Finishes]] (DNFs), two second-place finishes and one third place.<ref name="NASCARStatistics1973" /> At the first Rockingham event, Pearson led 499 of 500 miles, giving up the lead only for a pit stop.<ref name="Fleischman56">Fleischman, page 56</ref> He won eight pole positions with a 3.4 average starting position.<ref name="NASCARStatistics1973" />

Pearson finished third in the 1974 points after competing in 19 of 30 events.<ref name="Fleischman58">Fleischman, page 58</ref> It was the only season where drivers were awarded points based on their money earnings, which ended up rewarding drivers who finished high in the big-money races.<ref name="Fleischman57">Fleischman, page 57</ref> He won seven races, including the Winston 500 by 0.17 seconds over [[Benny Parsons]].<ref name="Fleischman58" /> Pearson earned some of his "outfox" nickname at the 1974 [[Coke Zero 400|Firecracker 400]]. Entering the final lap, he was leading followed closely by Petty. Fearing that Petty to do a [[slingshot pass]], he slowed a little, pulled his car off to the side to simulate a blown motor, and threw his hand up in the air as a motion of defeat. Petty quickly passed, only to find Pearson following him closely. Coming out of the final corner, Pearson did a slingshot pass back to win the race.<ref name=Ganchy>{{cite book|last=Ganchy|first=Sally|title=Great Moments in NASCAR Racing|publisher=Rosen Publishing Group|date=2008|pages=8-10|isbn=9781404213975|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ghnGM8iY_qIC&pg=PA7&dq=%22david+pearson%22+nascar#v=onepage&q=%22david%20pearson%22%20nascar&f=false|accessdate=2009-11-21}}</ref> The [[International Race of Champions]] (IROC) invited him to participate in their [[IROC I|first]] annual all-star [[stock car racing|stock car]] racing series for the 1973/74 season and he finished fourth of the twelve drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/yeardet?yr=1974&series=I|title=1973-74 IROC drivers standings|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

In 1975, NASCAR changed to the points system that it would use for over a decade until the current [[Chase for the Cup]] format was implemented.<ref name="Fleischman58" /> [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] televised the second half of the [[1975 Daytona 500]] and drew a 10.5 rating opposite a 8.6 rating for an [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] game and a 4.1 for a [[National Hockey League|NHL]] game.<ref name="Fleischman59">Fleischman, page 59</ref> Pearson led the race with three laps remaining. [[Benny Parsons]] was racing in a distant second. Petty, who was several laps down after experiencing tires difficulties, began [[drafting]] with Parsons and the duo started closing on Pearson. Pearson collided with another car and Parsons won the race. After the race, Pearson complained that Petty showed favoritism by helping Parsons.<ref name=Falk71 /> Pearson's attempt to win his third consecutive Winston 500 fell short when he was unable to catch Baker.<ref name="Fleischman59" /> Despite these near wins, he was able to win three times in 21 attempts.<ref name="Fleischman59" /> He finished 14th in points in the 30&ndash;event season.<ref name="Fleischman59" /> He competed in the [[IROC II|second annual IROC season]] during 1974/75 and he finished sixth in points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1975&series=I|title=1974-75 IROC drivers standings|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>
[[File:DavidPearson21Mercury.jpg|thumb|right|Pearson's #21 Mercury owned by the [[Wood Brothers]]]]
The [[1976 Daytona 500]] is know for the final lap battle between Pearson and Petty.<ref name="Fleischman60">Fleischman, page 60</ref> In 2007, [[ESPN]] rated the race as the fourth most interesting Daytona 500.<ref name="ESPNFeb152007">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/columns/story?seriesId=2&columnist=blount_terry&id=2763418|title=No. 4 most memorable Daytona 500: The crash|last=Blount|first=Terry|date=February 15, 2007|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=19 December 2009}}</ref> Petty passed Pearson for the lead at the beginning of the final lap.<ref name="Falk734">Falk, page 73-4</ref> Pearson used the draft to attempt a slingshot pass against Petty at the end of the back stretch,<ref name="Falk734" /> but his car [[understeer|pushed]] high into the final turn while going around another car. Petty edged under Pearson, and their cars crashed into each other on the frontstretch in the final turns.<ref name="Falk734" /> They both spun out into the infield grass approximately 100 feet (30 meters) short of the finish line.<ref name="Falk734" /> The third place car was over a lap behind the disabled cars.<ref name="Falk734" /> With Petty unable to restart his car, Pearson slowly drove his Wood Brothers Mercury over the grassy infield past the finish line for his only Daytona 500 victory.<ref name="Fleischman60" /><ref name="Ganchy" /> He won a series-best ten races in 1976, but finished ninth in season points after competing in only 22 of 30 events.<ref name="Fleischman61">Fleischman, page 61</ref> He won his only IROC race at the first race of [[IROC III]] in 1975/1976 at [[Michigan International Speedway]] and finished fifth in points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1976&series=I|title=1975-76 IROC drivers standings|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

Pearson finished 13th in the 1977 NASCAR points, with two wins in 22 (of 30) races.<ref name="Fleischman62">Fleischman, page 62</ref> IROC invited him to participate in [[IROC IV]] in 1976/77 and he finished ninth in the four race series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1977&series=I|title=1976-77 IROC drivers standings|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

He competed in 22 races (of 30) again in 1978, winning four times for a 16th place finish in the season points.<ref name="Fleischman63">Fleischman, page 63</ref> In March, Pearson won his 100th Winston Cup race at Rockingham.<ref name="Fleischman63" /> Late in the [[World 600]], Pearson was battling for the win against Parsons until Parsons' spin collected both drivers. [[Darrell Waltrip]] edged [[Donnie Allison]] for the victory.<ref name="Fleischman63" /> Pearson competed in his final IROC race in June 1978 during [[IROC V]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/driver?id=pearsda01|title=IROC drivers standings|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref>

Pearson began 1979 by winning the pole position at year's first race at Riverside; he finished the final NASCAR race at the track in second place.<ref name="RacingReference1979" /> 1979 was Pearson's final season racing for the Wood Brothers,<ref name="NASCARDavidPearson" /> with his last race happening at Darlington.<ref name="RacingReference1979">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1979&series=W|title=1979 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> After a miscommunication, he left the pits without waiting for the pit crew to place [[lugnut]]s on the car and the tires fell off the car when he reached the end of pit lane.<ref name="CrossWords">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2005/news/opinion/12/12/cross.words.pearson/index.html|title=Cross' Words: Pearson remains gold standard|last=Cross|first=B. Duane|date=December 12, 2005|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=19 January 2010}}</ref> Pearson quit the team after the race.<ref name="CrossWords" /> Pearson had won 43 races between 1972 and 79 while driving for the Wood Brothers.<ref name="NASCARDavidPearson" /> Later during the season, [[Rod Osterlund]]'s rookie driver, [[Dale Earnhardt]], suffered a shoulder injury.<ref name="CrossWords" /> Osterlund hired Pearson to replace Earnhardt during four races; he collected the pole position at Michigan and won the 1979 [[Mountain Dew Southern 500|Southern 500]].<ref name="RacingReference1979" /><ref name="CrossWords" /> For the season, Pearson had competed in nine races and finished 32nd in points.<ref name="Fleischman66">Fleischman, page 66</ref> Fans voted him as [[NASCAR's Most Popular Driver Award|NASCAR's Most Popular Driver]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/kyn/history/data/popular_driver.html|title=History: Most Popular Driver|date=2007|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=2009-11-16}}</ref>

===1980s===
Pearson raced for [[Hoss Ellington]] during the 1980 season.<ref name="RacingReference1980">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1980&series=W|title=1980 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He won the 1980 [[Rebel 500|CRC Chemicals Rebel 500]] at Darlington for his final Cup win.<ref name="CrossWords" /> He started nine times to finish 37th in season points.<ref name="Fleischman77">Fleischman, page 77</ref><ref name="RacingReferenceCareer">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/driver?id=pearsda01|title=David Pearson career NASCAR driving statistics|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> Pearson qualified on the [[pole position]] at Charlotte for his eleventh straight time and he had started on the front row in fifteen straight races between 1972-80.<ref name="NASCARCareerSoars" /> In 1981, he raced in six races for four owners.<ref name="RacingReference1981">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1981&series=W|title=1981 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> His season was highlighted by winning the pole position for Kennie Childers at Dover and two Top 10 finishes at Darlington.<ref name="RacingReference1981" />

Bobby Hawkins hired Pearson to race in six events during 1982.<ref name="RacingReference1982">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1982&series=W|title=1982 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He started on the pole position at Charlotte and Darlington and had top five finishes at the July Daytona race and Charlotte.<ref name="RacingReference1982" /> He ended the 30-race season in 37th place in the point standings.<ref name="RacingReference1982" /> Pearson entered his first NASCAR Busch Grand National (now [[Nationwide Series]]) race that season.<ref name="NASCARDrivingStastistics">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/hof/dpearson00/|title=David Pearson driving statistics|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=12 December 2009}}</ref> He won the pole position for that race at Bristol and he finished second.<ref name="NASCAR1982Stats">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/hof/dpearson00/seasons/1982.html|title=1982 season results|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=12 December 2009}}</ref> Pearson raced in two more Busch races that season (Dover, North Carolina), starting second and first; he finished fifth and first.<ref name="NASCAR1982Stats" /> The North Carolina win was his only Busch victory.<ref name="NASCARDrivingStastistics" />

Pearson raced in ten events for Hawkins in 1983.<ref name="RacingReference1983">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1983&series=W|title=1983 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He had four top ten finishes, including eighth and third place finishes at Daytona, and finished 33rd in points.<ref name="RacingReference1983" /> Pearson started from the pole position for his final Busch Grand National race at Dover; it resulted in a twelfth place finish.<ref name="NASCAR1983Stats">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/hof/dpearson00/seasons/1983.html|title=1983 season results|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=12 December 2009}}</ref> In 1984, Pearson raced in eleven events for Hawkins and finished 41st in the season points.<ref name="NASCAR1984">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/dps/dpearson00/cup/data/1984/index.html|title=1984 Driver's statistics|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=2009-11-16}}</ref><ref name="Fleischman83">Fleischman, page 83</ref> He had three top ten finishes, all ninth place finishes, at the [[1984 Daytona 500|Daytona 500]], [[World 600]], and the [[Miller 400]].<ref name="NASCAR1984" />

Pearson raced in twelve races during 1985, the first eight for Hoss Ellington and the final four for himself.<ref name="RacingReference1985">{{cite web|url=http://racing-reference.info/drivdet?id=pearsda01&yr=1985&series=W|title=1985 David Pearson race results|publisher=Racing Reference|accessdate=2009-11-15}}</ref> He had an average start of 9.2, but ten DNFs resulted in an average finish over 30th place.<ref name="RacingReference1985" /> He had one top ten finish at the July Daytona race and finished 36th in points.<ref name="RacingReference1985" /><ref name="Fleischman84">Fleischman, page 84</ref> 1986 was Pearson's final season in NASCAR. Pearson drove his own car in two events. After a DNF at Charlotte, he finished tenth in his final race at the August Michigan event.<ref name="NASCAR 1986">{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/drivers/dps/dpearson00/cup/data/1986/index.html|title=1986 Driver's statistics|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=2009-11-16}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The [[National Motor Sports Press Association]]'s Hall of Fame inducted Pearson in 1991.<ref name="NASCARDavidPearson" /> He was inducted in the [[International Motorsports Hall of Fame]] in 1993 and the [[Lowes Motor Speedway|Charlotte Motor Speedway]] Court of Legends in 1998.<ref name="NASCARDavidPearson" /> He was one of ten finalists for the Driver of the Quarter Century (1967-1991) sponsored by a United States businessman; [[Mario Andretti]] won the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/07/sports/sports-people-auto-racing-andretti-is-honored.html?scp=33&sq=%22david+pearson%22&st=nyt|title=Andretti Is Honored|date=1992-10-07|publisher=[[New York Times]]|pages=B12|accessdate=12 December 2009}}</ref> In the middle of 1999, [[Sports Illustrated]] used votes from 40 NASCAR insiders to name Pearson was named the Top Sports Car Driver of the Twentieth Century.<ref name="SC CR 4658">{{cite web|url=www.scstatehouse.gov/sess113_1999-2000/bills/4658.doc|title=South Carolina Concurrent Resolution  4658|date=2000|publisher=[[South Carolina]]|accessdate=14 February 2010|format=DOC}}</ref>

In 2009, Pearson was one of the 25 nominees for the first class to be inducted in the [[NASCAR Hall of Fame]].<ref name="USAToday20090702">{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/nascar/2009-07-02-hall-of-fame-nominees_N.htm|title=NASCAR Hall of Fame nominees a who's who of stars|date=2009-07-02|publisher=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=2009-08-20}}</ref> NASCAR named the five people to be inducted in its 2010 class and it stated that he finished between sixth and eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2009/news/opinion/10/14/one.menz.jmenzer.hall.of.fame.class/index.html|title=Pearson's exclusion the surprise of inaugural vote|last=Menzer|first=Joe|date=October 14, 2009|publisher=NASCAR|accessdate=14 December 2009}}</ref> Pearson left the premises ten minutes after the inductees were announced.<ref name="SportsIllustratedOctober152009">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_bowles/10/15/hall.of.fame/index.html|title=Pearson, Yarborough top list for NASCAR Hall of Fame class of 2011|last=Bowles|first=Tom|date=October 15, 2009|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=22 December 2009}}</ref> The snub drew public criticism with some writers predicted that he will be the headliner for the 2011 class.<ref name="ESPNOctober162009" /><ref name="SportsIllustratedOctober152009" />

==Personal life==
Pearson's wife Helen R. Pearson was deceased in 2000.<ref name="SC CR 4658" /> He has three sons ([[Larry Pearson]], Ricky Pearson, and Eddie Pearson).<ref name="SC CR 4658" /> Larry raced in NASCAR and he was the 1986 Busch Series champion. Ricky Pearson was general manager and a crew chief for [[Buckshot Jones]]/[[Buckshot Racing]] when they won two Busch Series races.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19990115&id=h4QUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=swMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6526,6051679|title=Buckshot at the Big Time|date=1999-01-15|publisher=[[Associated Press]] / [[Toledo Blade]]|accessdate=21 November 2009}}</ref>

